         <abstract>
            <p>In this paper we consider the problem of computing 2-D Cauchy principal value integrals of the form &lt;tex-math&gt;$\int_S F(P_0; P)dP,\quad P_0 \in S,$&lt;/tex-math&gt; where S is either a rectangle or a triangle, and F(P&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt;; P) is integrable over S, except at the point P&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; where it has a second-order pole. Using polar coordinates, the integral is first reduced to the form ∫&lt;sup&gt;θ&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;θ&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/sub&gt; ∫&lt;sup&gt;R(θ)&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; f(r, θ)/r dr dθ, where ∫ denotes the finite part of the (divergent) integral. Then ad hoc products of one-dimensional quadrature rules of Gaussian type are constructed, and corresponding convergence results derived. Some numerical tests are also presented.</p>
          </abstract>
